body:
I've assumed that the `children` would always inherit the context from its parent, but that's not always the case:

This works as expected:

``` jsx
// child
class Child extends React.Component {
    static contextTypes = { color: React.PropTypes.bool };
    render() {
        const style = { color: this.context.color };
        return <div style={{color: this.context.color}}>Children color is {this.context.color}</div>
    }
}
// parent
class Parent extends React.Component {
    static childContextTypes = { color: React.PropTypes.string };
    getChildContext() {
        return { color: 'red' };
    }
    render() {
        return <div><Child /></div>;
    }   
}
React.render(<Parent />, document.getElementById('root'));
```

But if change the parent to use `this.props.children`, the context is not transferred to its children anymore:

``` jsx
// parent using this.props.children
class Parent extends React.Component {
    ...
    render() {
        return <div>{this.props.children}</div>;
    }   
}
React.render(<Parent><Child /></Parent>, document.getElementById('root'));
```

I've also created simple [jsfiddle](http://jsfiddle.net/p23w9Laz/) to demonstrate that.

I would assume that if the `<Child>` is inside the parent, it should inherit the context of it.
Is that how it's meant to be? And is there a way to change the context, so the second example would also work?
